abstract = {In this paper we describe a study exploring why users spend more time in email than
originally intended, which we call getting lost in email. To study this phenomenon,
we implemented an IMAP logger that also dispatched diary entries to collect data for
twenty participants over a two week period. Most participants reported getting lost
in email during both short and long sessions. Our analysis suggests two primary factors
in getting lost: the number of emails awaiting a reply and whether or not the session
caused an interruption. We conclude that much of the problem around getting lost in
email is in managing the tension between promptly responding to messages while limiting
engagement with email.},
