we present our work with several open source DIYbio tools, including OpenPCR and Pearl
Blue Transilluminator, which can be used to test DNA samples for specific sequences.
We frame these platforms as things that gather heterogeneous materials and concerns,
and enable new forms of knowledge transfer. Working with these hybrid systems in professional
and DIY settings, we conducted a workshop where non-biologists tested food products
for genetic modifications. Our findings suggest new design directions at the intersection
of biology, technology, and DIY: i) DIYbio platforms as rich tools for hybrid knowledge
production; and ii) open source biology as a site for public engagement with science.},
booktitle = {Proceedings of the 33rd Annual ACM Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems},
