where the effect of clutching on pointing performance is dissociated from the effects
of control-to-display transfer functions. Participants performed a series of target
acquisition tasks using typical cursor acceleration functions with and without clutching.
All pointing tasks were feasible without clutching, but clutch-less movements were
harder to perform, caused more errors, required more preparation time, and were not
faster than clutch-enabled movements.},
